Water Level Model Analysis

Analysis of ecological context variables and regression models for prediction the relationship (slope) between lake water level and cummulative precipitation deviation using 39 Lake dataset generated on Feb. 21 2019.

Initial Data

dat <- regressionstats %>% left_join(ecocontext_full) %>% select(-W_LAT,
                                                                 -MeanDepth,
                                                                 -SHAPE_AREA,
                                                                 -W_AREA,
                                                                 -W_PRCP_ANN,
                                                                 -W_TEMP_ANN,
                                                                 -W_TEMP_GS,
                                                                 -W_TEMP_JUL,
                                                                 -mg_average,
                                                                 -ca_average) %>% 
    select_if(~ !any(is.na(.)))
## Joining, by = "WiscID"

Removed several variables that were duplicated along with ones that have missing values and/or are not of interest initially.

Correlated Variables

Identify correlations between all pairs of ecocontext variables

dat.ld <- dat[,c(10:ncol(dat))]
x <- dat.ld %>%
    correlate() %>%    # Create correlation data frame (cor_df)
    rearrange() %>%  # rearrange by correlations
    shave() # Shave off the upper triangle for a clean result

Random Forest Model for variable selection using the VSURF Package

out <- VSURF(x=dat.ld,y=dat$slope,ntree=10000,nfor.thres = 1000,nfor.interp = 500,nfor.pred = 500,parallel = T)
names(dat.ld)[out$varselect.thres]

dat.ld = dat[,names(dat.ld)[out$varselect.interp]]
models <- regsubsets(x = dat.ld,y = dat$slope,nbest = 8)
plot(models)

#identify best model based on different criteria
res.sum <- summary(models)
sum.out <- data.frame(
    model = 1:length(res.sum$adjr2),
    Adj.R2 = (res.sum$adjr2),
    CP = (res.sum$cp),
    BIC = (res.sum$bic)
) %>% arrange(BIC) %>% 
  filter((min(BIC)-BIC) >=-2)
sum.out
